        heading: 'COBie in the Philippine Context',
        content: "COBie adoption in the Philippines is at an early stage at the time of this course. Large international projects and joint ventures with international FM operators are most likely to specify COBie in their EIRs. DPWH projects have not yet mandated COBie output as a standard requirement, though this may change as the BIM roadmap matures.\n\nFor Philippine BIM professionals, the practical skill of producing reliable COBie output from Revit — setting up shared parameters, configuring families, and managing data completion throughout a project — is a differentiating capability. It positions you to work on the most technically demanding projects and to advise clients who are beginning to think about lifecycle information management.\n\nEven on projects that do not formally require COBie, the COBie schema is a useful reference for what operational asset data matters. Using it as a checklist for what parameters to populate in a Revit model — even if the output format is not formally COBie — improves the usefulness of the model for any handover scenario."
